        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Introduction",
            "subtitle": "Why GNU and GNOME Matter",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "Modern computing is dominated by proprietary software, yet much of the digital world quietly runs on free and open-source foundations. GNU and GNOME are two such foundational projects that emphasize freedom, collaboration, and user empowerment."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "Together, they demonstrate how software can be developed ethically while still shaping global technology infrastructure."
                }
            ],
            "notes": "Explain free software philosophy briefly before moving forward."
        },
        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "What is GNU?",
            "subtitle": "A Free Software Movement",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "GNU is a free software operating system initiated in 1983 by Richard Stallman. The goal of the GNU Project was to create a completely free Unix-like operating system."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "bullets",
                    "items": [
                        "GNU stands for 'GNU's Not Unix'",
                        "Emphasizes software freedom over convenience",
                        {
                            "text": "Four essential freedoms",
                            "subpoints": [
                                "Run the program for any purpose",
                                "Study how the program works",
                                "Redistribute copies",
                                "Modify and distribute improvements"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "GNU Philosophy",
            "subtitle": "Freedom as a Technical and Moral Value",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "The GNU philosophy treats software freedom as a civil liberty. According to this view, proprietary software creates power imbalance by preventing users from understanding or controlling the tools they depend on."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "bullets",
                    "items": [
                        "Opposes digital restrictions management (DRM)",
                        "Rejects software surveillance",
                        "Promotes ethical computing"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "What is GNOME?",
            "subtitle": "A Desktop for Humans",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "GNOME is a free and open-source desktop environment designed to provide a simple, accessible, and distraction-free user experience. It is widely used in GNU/Linux systems."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "bullets",
                    "items": [
                        "Focus on simplicity and usability",
                        "Designed with accessibility in mind",
                        {
                            "text": "Used by major platforms",
                            "subpoints": [
                                "Fedora Linux",
                                "Debian",
                                "Ubuntu (earlier versions)"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "GNOME Design Principles",
            "subtitle": "Less, But Better",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "GNOME follows a human-centered design philosophy. Instead of offering endless customization, it prioritizes consistency, clarity, and reduced cognitive load."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "bullets",
                    "items": [
                        "Minimalist interface",
                        "Keyboard-driven workflows",
                        "Strong accessibility standards"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "GNU + Linux + GNOME",
            "subtitle": "How the Stack Comes Together",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "kind": "paragraph",
                    "text": "In practice, GNU provides system tools, Linux provides the kernel, and GNOME provides the user interface. Together, they form a complete free operating system experience."
                },
                {
                    "kind": "table",
                    "columns": [
                        "Layer",
                        "Component",
